                      <cell role="data">http://syriaca.org/taxonomy/syrian-catholics</cell>
                      <cell role="data">Syrian Catholics</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row role="data">
                      <cell role="data">http://syriaca.org/taxonomy/syrian-orthodox</cell>
                      <cell role="data">Syrian Orthodox</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row role="data">
                      <cell role="data">http://syriaca.org/taxonomy/twelver</cell>
                      <cell role="data">Twelver</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row role="data">
                      <cell role="data">http://syriaca.org/taxonomy/west-syrian-church</cell>
                      <cell role="data">West Syrian Church</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row role="data">
                      <cell role="data">http://syriaca.org/taxonomy/yezidis</cell>
                      <cell role="data">Yezidis</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row role="data">
                      <cell role="data">http://syriaca.org/taxonomy/zaydi</cell>
                      <cell role="data">Zaydi</cell>
                    </row>
                    <row role="data">
                      <cell role="data">http://syriaca.org/taxonomy/zoroastrians</cell>
                      <cell role="data">Zoroastrians</cell>
                    </row>
                  </table>
                </p>
                  <p>The following is an example of a properly-encoded confession state: <egXML
                    xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                    <state type="confession" xml:id="confession78-1"
                      ref="http://syriaca.org/taxonomy/syrian-orthodox" from="0451" to="1924"
                      source="#bib78-1">
                      <desc xml:lang="en">Syrian Orthodox</desc>
                    </state>
                  </egXML>
                  The above example also demonstrates that confession states should be sourced
                  according to the guidelines on <ref target="#source">Inserting Citations</ref>. As
                  well, confessions may optionally include attributes to express temporal
                  constraints on the assertion of the presence of a confessional community in a
                  place as described in <ref target="#dates">Recording Date Information for Occurrences and Durations</ref>.
                  In the preceding example, the <att>from</att> and <att>to</att> attributes
                  indicate that Syrian Orthodox communities were present at Edessa between 451 and
                  1924 CE.</p>
              </div>
              <div xml:id="existence">
                <head>Existence and Duration (<gi>state</gi>)</head>
                <p>Assertions of the existence of a place, and the duration of that existence, are
                  made using a <gi>state</gi> element with a <att>type</att> of "existence". These
                  elements require source information following the guidlines for <ref
                    target="#source">Inserting Citations</ref>. At the most basic level, this
                  element asserts that a place has existed, or continues exist. Example: <egXML
                    xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                    <state resp="http://syriaca.org" type="existence"/>
                  </egXML> The duration of a place's existence can be qualified using the temporal
                  attributes described in the <ref target="#dates">Recording Date Information for Occurrences and Durations</ref>
                  section; as well, the (un)certainty of a temoral qualification can be expressed as described in the 
                  <ref target="#datePrecision">Recording Uncertainty for Event and Status Dates (<gi>precision</gi>)</ref> section.
                  An example existence state, demonstrating the above encoding options, follows:
                  <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                    <state resp="http://syriaca.org" type="existence" from="0306" to="2013">
                      <precision match="@from" notAfter="0306"/>
                      <precision match="@to" notBefore="2013"/>
                    </state>
                  </egXML>
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div xml:id="note">
              <head>Scholarly Annotation (<gi>note</gi>)</head>
              <p><emph>This element is not required. A record may have any number of <gi>note</gi>
                  elements.</emph></p>
              <p><title>TSG</title> employs the <gi>note</gi> element for two different purposes:
                deprecation of a name variant and the encoding of information that is uncertain or
                incorrect.</p>
              <p>All <gi>note</gi> elements must have an <att>xml:lang</att> attribute indicating
                the language of the note. In most cases this will be "en" for English but other
                languages can be indicated as needed.
                (for more details, see <ref target="#languageCodes">Recording Language Information</ref>).
                Notes should also be sourced, as described in <ref target="#source">Inserting Bibliographic Citations</ref>, though they will most likely
                use a <att>resp</att> attribute as they tend to be assertions made by the contributors rather than
                cited to a particular source (cf. <ref target="#resp">Asserting Information without a Source</ref>).
                These scholarly annotations should be written as complete sentences with proper punctuation.</p>
              <div xml:id="deprecation">
                <head>Deprecated Names (<gi>note</gi>)</head>
                <p>Certain names reported in our database are patently erroneous (e.g. <foreign
                    xml:lang="syr">ܛܘܪܳܐ ܕܩܰܐܣܒܘܢ</foreign> for <q>Mount Qāsiyūn</q>, URI: <ref
                    target="http://syriaca.org/place/518"
                    ><code>http://syriaca.org/place/518</code></ref>, instead of <foreign
                    xml:lang="syr">ܛܘܪܳܐ ܕܩܰܐܣܝܘܢ</foreign>; in this case the error is based on the
                  translator mis-reading an Arabic letter ba for ya). We need to preserve these
                  erroneous names in our data for historical reasons, so that the right place can be
                  found as a search result even if someone searches on the basis of an erroneous
                  print resource or now deprecated name. Nevertheless, the editors do not wish to
                  assert implicitly or explicitly that this is an "acceptable alternate" form of the
                  name. In order to mark the <gi>placeName</gi> element as erroneous, we create a
                    <gi>note</gi> element with a <att>type</att> attribute whose value must be <q>deprecation</q>. The content of
                  the <gi>note</gi> element provides a detailed explanation of why this name is considered
                  deprecated. In order to link the <gi>note</gi> element to the corresponding
                    <gi>placeName</gi> element containing the deprecated name variant, an <att>target</att> attribute whose value is the
                    <att>xml:id</att> value for the deprecated <gi>placeName</gi> element is included in
                  the <gi>note</gi> element separated by whitespace if there are links to multiple names for
                  the same reason in the note. To preserve the valid sequence of elements in a <title>TSG</title>
                  record, the <gi>note</gi> element indicating the deprecation should occur immediately
                  before the <gi>idno</gi> section.</p>
                <p>In the HTML display of the record, deprecated names are removed from
                  the list of names and instead listed in a Deprecations section at the
                  bottom of the record, to warn users that these forms are retained for historical
                  and provenance reasons, but should not be used as acceptable name variants.</p>
                <p>Example: <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                    <place type="settlement" ana="http://syriaca.org/taxonomy/settlements">
                      <placeName xml:id="name496-3" xml:lang="syr-Syrj" source="#bib496-1">ܦܰܢܺܝܗ</placeName>
                      ...
                      <note target="#name496-3" xml:lang="en" type="deprecation" resp="http://syriaca.org">
                        Dolabani or his printer dropped off the first consonant of the name.
                      </note>
                    </place>
                  </egXML>
                </p>
              </div>
              <div xml:id="disputanda">
                <head>Disputanda (<gi>note</gi>)</head>
                <p>As with the inclusion of deprecated name variants, it is sometimes necessary to report in a
                  place record information which is either known to be incorrect or which is
                  contested in the scholarly literature. In these cases, editors should signal this
                  information with a <gi>note</gi> element before the <gi>idno</gi> element(s). The
                  content of the <gi>note</gi> element should provide a description of the incorrect or disputed assertion,
                  using as diplomatic a formulation as possible, in particular avoiding naming living
                  scholars to curtail multiplying scholarly contention. The <gi>note</gi> element must
                  have a <att>type</att> attribute with one of several values. The value "incerta" 
                  should be used to report scholarly uncertainty or disagreement about an assertion. 
                  The value "corrigenda" should be used to report typographical errors or other equally 
                  mechanistic problems which can be easily fixed. The value "errata" should only be used for 
                  <gi>note</gi> elements if there is a clear and undisputed error whose solution is not obvious.</p>
                <p>The examples below, drawn from different places, illustrate these various uses of the <gi>note</gi> element:
                  <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                    <note xml:lang="en" type="incerta" resp="http://syriaca.org"> GEDSH article
                      identifies its river as the <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/43"
                        >Balikh</placeName>, but the identification is contested. </note>
                  </egXML>
                  <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                    <note xml:lang="en" type="corrigenda"> In Dolabani's translation of Barsoum's
                      description <quote xml:lang="syr-Syrj">ܒܓܰܪܓܪܰ</quote> should read <quote
                        xml:lang="syr-Syrj">ܒܓܰܪܓܰܪ</quote>. </note>
                  </egXML>
                  <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                    <note xml:lang="en" type="corrigenda" resp="http://syriaca.org"> GEDSH Map II
                      displays the location too far to the south, east of <placeName
                        ref="http://syriaca.org/place/91">Ḥama</placeName> rather than west of
                        <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/18">Aleppo</placeName>. </note>
                  </egXML>
                  <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                    <note xml:lang="en" type="corrigenda" resp="http://syriaca.org"> Moosa's English
                      translation of Barsoum's description was incorrectly published under the
                      headword "Samosata," while his description under the headword "Arsamosata" in
                      fact describes the village <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/442"
                        >Kaʿbiya</placeName>. </note>
                  </egXML>
                  <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                    <note xml:lang="en" type="errata" resp="http://syriaca.org"> Barsoum's
                      description erroneously merges the information for this location with that of
                      the other <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/571">Mor Bosus</placeName>,
                      which is located between Apamea and Ḥomṣ. </note>
                  </egXML>
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div xml:id="idno">
              <head>Identifiers (<gi>idno</gi>)</head>
              <p><emph>This element is required. A record must have at least one <gi>idno</gi>
                  indicating a Syriaca.org URI. Records belonging to more than one Syriaca.org
                  publication, must have an <gi>idno</gi> for each publication. A record may have
                  any number of additional <gi>idno</gi> elements.</emph></p>
              <p>As discussed above in the section on the <ref target="#concept">Concept of a
                  Place</ref>, URIs are an important part of delineating a place. Each place record
                needs one or more <gi>idno</gi> elements to indicate the URIs which refer to this
                place. Each <gi>idno</gi> element will have a <att>type</att> attribute with value
                "URI", and the first should encapsulate the Syriaca.org URI for the place:
                <code>http://syriaca.org/place/{\d+}</code>. If a place record belongs to other publications
                of Syriaca.org, it may receive a distinct URI related to those publications. For example,
                places in the <title>Gazetteer to John of Ephesus’s Ecclesiastical History</title>, a sub-volume of
                <title>TSG</title>, should have an additional <gi>idno</gi> element with the sub-volume's URI.
                Other <gi>idno</gi> elements with
                a <att>type</att> attribute of "URI" will encapsulate any Pleiades URI for this place as well as
                any Wikipedia URL(s) which refer to this place. In particular, if the same place is
                the topic of separate Wikipedia articles divided by time period, both or all such
                articles will have their URLs listed here. If desired, a link to a DBpedia resource
                URI can be encapsulated within an <gi>idno</gi> element of <att>type</att>="URI",
                but care should be exercised only to link to the DBpedia resource URI when the place
                is the subject of only one Wikipedia article, and when the type of place described
                by that article is the same as the type of place in our database (it is very common
                for Wikipedia articles to be about a modern country rather than a historical region,
                for example, or for village Wikipedia articles found in modern Turkey to be about "a
                district" rather than about the village itself). If there is any doubt that the
                DBpedia resource URI and the Syriaca.org URI are speaking of an identical place in
                all contexts, it is better to omit the DBpedia URI. </p>
              <p> The URIs of Edessa (the essential one from Syriaca.org, one from the <title>Gazetteer to John of Ephesus’s Ecclesiastical History</title>, 
                one from Pleiades, and two different Wikipedia articles) can be represented as follows:
                <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                  <idno type="URI">http://syriaca.org/place/78</idno>
                  <idno type="URI">http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/658457</idno>
                  <idno type="URI">http://syriaca.org/johnofephesus/places/78</idno>
                  <idno type="URI">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edessa</idno>
                  <idno type="URI">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Şanlıurfa</idno>
                </egXML>
              </p>
            </div>
            <div xml:id="bibl">
              <head><q>Works Cited</q> (<gi>bibl</gi>)</head>
              <!-- WLP, should we add some subsections here? Such as break out citedRange? DAM -->
              <p><emph>This element is required. A record must have at least one <gi>bibl</gi>
                  element documenting the existence of the place as a concept. A record may have any
                  number of additional <gi>bibl</gi> elements.</emph></p>
              <p>Syriaca.org manages the publication information for all citations in a separate
                reference work, <ref target="https://syriaca.org/cbss/index.html"><title>The
                    Comprehensive Bibliography on Syriac Studies (CBSS)</title></ref>. Accordingly,
                the first step in adding a citation into a record in <title>TSG</title> is to
                identify the corresponding entry in <title>CBSS</title>. Users can search the
                bibliography at <ref target="https://syriaca.org/cbss/search.html"
                  >https://syriaca.org/cbss/search.html</ref>. Once the item to be cited is located,
                authors should note the URI for the bibliographic item. This URI will have the
                format <code>http://syriaca.org/cbss/[A-Z0-9]{8}$</code> (where
                  <code>[A-Z0-9]{8}$</code> signifies a unique string of 8 uppercase alphanumeric
                characters). For example, the URI for J.B. Segal, <title>Edessa, ‘The Blessed
                  City’</title> (Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1970) is <ref
                  target="http://syriaca.org/cbss/FQCVBMNS"
                    ><code>http://syriaca.org/cbss/FQCVBMNS</code></ref>. If the desired
                bibliographic item is not found in <title>CBSS</title>, authors should request the
                creation of an entry in <title>CBSS</title>. </p>
              <p>After ascertaining the <title>CBSS</title> URI, the next step is add an entry for
                that item in the <q>Works Cited</q> section of the place record in
                  <title>TSG</title>. Each bibliographic item cited should be marked up as a
                separate <gi>bibl</gi> element. The purpose of the <gi>bibl</gi> element is to
                provide three linking functions: <list>
                  <item>to the footnote number</item>
                  <item>to the <title>CBSS</title> URI for the cited item</item>
                  <item>to the specific page numbers or other cited range within that item</item>
                </list>Here is an example of a <gi>bibl</gi> record: <egXML
                  xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                  <bibl xml:id="bib78-24">
                    <ptr target="http://syriaca.org/bibl/FQCVBMNS"/>
                    <citedRange unit="p">82-87</citedRange>
                  </bibl>
                </egXML>
              </p>
              <p>Each <gi>bibl</gi> element must have a unique xml:id, as shown in the above example.
                This ID used is used to identify the citation internally in the <q>Works Cited</q> list for the place
                record. The attribute value for the <att>xml:id</att> attribute is in the format
                  <code>bib{\d+}-{\d+}</code>, where the first number is derived from the
                Syriaca.org URI for the place (i.e. using the final unique numeric element in the
                URI) and the second number is a sequential integer representing the order of this
                  <gi>bibl</gi> element in the series of <gi>bibl</gi> elements contained in this
                place record, beginning from 1. In the preceding example, the twenty-fourth <gi>bibl</gi>
                element within the place record describing Edessa (URI <ref
                  target="https://syriaca.org/place/78">https://syriaca.org/place/78</ref>) leads to
                the following xml:id value "bib78-24". The second numeric value (in this case "24")
                will also serve as the number for the footnote in the HTML view of the record.</p>
              <p>Next the example above illustrates how the <gi>bibl</gi> also has a required
                  <gi>ptr</gi> (pointer) element which provides the link externally to the
                  <title>CBSS</title> URI, encoded as the value of the <att>target</att> attribute. In this
                case the URI is <code>http://syriaca.org/bibl/FQCVBMNS</code>. An automated script
                will use this URI link to insert the full publication information into the HTML view
                of the <title>TSG</title> record.</p>
              <p>Lastly, this example above indicates a specific page range using the optional but
                recommended <gi>citedRange</gi> element (and its required <att>unit</att>
                attribute). This cited range indicates ranges specific to the citations in this
                place record. If a place record contains multiple citations of the same
                bibliographic item, the cited ranges may all be combined into a single ascending
                cited range (for example "82-87, 90, 95-96"). Alternatively, should more precision of the
               cited range be required (such as if two name variants appear on different pages of the citation),
               multiple <gi>bibl</gi> elements linking to the same <title>CBSS</title> URI may be included in the "Works Cited" section,
              differing only by their <gi>citedRange</gi> element, as in the below example:
              <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                <place>
                  <placeName source="#bib108-10" xml:id="name108-1" xml:lang="en" srophe:tags="#syriaca-headword">Karka d-Beth Slokh</placeName>
                  <placeName source="#bib108-11" xml:id="name108-2" xml:lang="en">Kirkuk</placeName>
                  ...
                  <bibl xml:id="bib108-10">
                    <ptr target="http://syriaca.org/cbss/SYM5C6P5"/>
                    <citedRange unit="p">828</citedRange>
                  </bibl>
                  <bibl xml:id="bib108-11">
                    <ptr target="http://syriaca.org/cbss/SYM5C6P5"/>
                    <citedRange unit="p">829</citedRange>
                  </bibl>
                </place>
              </egXML>
                While the above is permitted, it is preffered where possible to limit the creation of <gi>bibl</gi>
                elements so that only one <gi>bibl</gi> per <title>CBSS</title> URI is included in a place record.
              </p>
              <p>Allowed values for <att>unit</att> are: <table rows="14" cols="2">
                  <head>Allowed Citation Range Unit Values</head>
                  <row role="label">
                    <cell role="label">Unit Value</cell>
                    <cell role="label">Description</cell>
                  </row>
                  <row role="data">
                    <cell role="data">book</cell>
                    <cell role="data">a book, typically a numbered portion of an ancient work</cell>
                  </row>
                  <row role="data">
                    <cell role="data">chapter</cell>
                    <cell role="data">a chapter by number, title, or both</cell>
                  </row>
                  <row role="data">
                    <cell role="data">col</cell>
                    <cell role="data">a column or column range</cell>
                  </row>
                  <row role="data">
                    <cell role="data">entry</cell>
                    <cell role="data">an entry in a collection such as an reference work</cell>
                  </row>
                  <row role="data">
                    <cell role="data">fig</cell>
                    <cell role="data">a figure, i.e. a graphic, table, etc.</cell>
                  </row>
                  <row role="data">
                    <cell role="data">fol</cell>
                    <cell role="data">a folio number or folio range</cell>
                  </row>
                  <row role="data">
                    <cell role="data">line</cell>
                    <cell role="data">a line number or line range</cell>
                  </row>
                  <row role="data">
                    <cell role="data">map</cell>
                    <cell role="data">a map</cell>
                  </row>
                  <row role="data">
                    <cell role="data">note</cell>
                    <cell role="data">a footnote or endnote</cell>
                  </row>
                  <row role="data">
                    <cell role="data">part</cell>
                    <cell role="data">a part of a book or collection, i.e. chapter and verse of a
                      biblical text</cell>
                  </row>
                  <row role="data">
                    <cell role="data">p</cell>
                    <cell role="data">a page number or page range</cell>
                  </row>
                  <row role="data">
                    <cell role="data">section</cell>
                    <cell role="data">a section of a text</cell>
                  </row>
                  <row role="data">
                    <cell role="data">URL</cell>
                    <cell role="data">a URL where information is located</cell>
                  </row>
                  <row role="data">
                    <cell role="data">vol</cell>
                    <cell role="data">a volume of a multi-volume work</cell>
                  </row>
                </table> These values remain the same even if the cited range is plural. When
                multiple page numbers are cited, they should be entered in full and never be
                abbreviated (thus "556-558" not "556-8").</p>
              <p>All of these <gi>bibl</gi> elements should be grouped together as the final child
                elements within the <gi>place</gi> element, as in this example: <egXML
                  xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                  <place>
                    <placeName>...</placeName>
                    <desc>...</desc>
                    <bibl xml:id="bib78-1">
                      <ptr target="http://syriaca.org/cbss/C5T777C3"/>
                      <citedRange unit="p">138-139</citedRange>
                    </bibl>
                    <bibl xml:id="bib78-2">
                      <ptr target="http://syriaca.org/cbss/P8KQJ7AE"/>
                      <citedRange unit="map">Map I B1, II B1, III</citedRange>
                    </bibl>
                    <bibl xml:id="bib78-3">
                      <ptr target="http://syriaca.org/cbss/SGBVKKGH"/>
                      <citedRange unit="p">556-558</citedRange>
                    </bibl>
                  </place>
                </egXML>
              </p>
              <p>In as much as is feasible, the <gi>bibl</gi> elements should be ordered based on
                the order of occurance of citation in the XML file. Thus the first bibliographic
                item to be cited would occur as the first <gi>bibl</gi> and the second item to be
                cited would occur as the second <gi>bibl</gi>, etc. At times, however, this order
                will not be strictly maintained. For example, if the first item to be cited is also
                cited again later in document, it would remain as the first <gi>bibl</gi> and does
                not need to be repeated. Simiarly, if a later revision of the record introduces
                citations of new bibliographic items in the middle of the record, authors should add
                the new bibliographic items below the existing <gi>bibl</gi> elements rather than
                attempting to re-order or re-number the <gi>bibl</gi> elements according to
                occurence. <emph>Nota bene:</emph> In these cases, the auto-generated footnote
                numbering used on the webpages for <title>TSG</title> entries will not follow
                standard numeric order (e.g., a reference to footnote 7 might precede the reference
                to footnote 6) but the citation numbers will nevertheless direct readers to the
                correct work cited.</p>
              <div xml:id="pleiades">
                <head>Sourcing Information from Pleiades, Wikipedia, etc.</head>
                <p>As noted in the <ref target="#idno">Identifiers</ref> section, above, records <title>TSG</title>
                  should link, where possible, to entries in other databases such as the <title>Pleiades Gazetteer</title>.
                  In some case, however, these entries may themselves be the source of information contained within the 
                <title>TSG</title> record. A common case is the inclusion of geographic coordinates from <title>Pleaides</title>.
                The <gi>bibl</gi> elements for these cases should follow the below structure.</p>
                <p>To facilitate sourcing this information, there is a bibliographic entry in <title>CBSS</title> for the full
                  Pleiades dataset: <ref target="http://syriaca.org/cbss/NAA6P8IX">http://syriaca.org/cbss/NAA6P8IX</ref>.
                  This URI should be used in the <att>target</att> attribute of the
                <gi>ptr</gi> element. The <gi>citedRange</gi> element should contain as its text node the URI of the entry in
                <title>Pleiades</title>, and its <att>unit</att> attribute should be <q>entry</q>. Additionally, the <gi>citedRange</gi>
                element must have a <att>target</att> attribute whose value is the <title>Pleiades</title> URI.</p>
                <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                  <bibl xml:id="bib100-6">
                    <ptr target="http://syriaca.org/cbss/NAA6P8IX"/>
                    <citedRange unit="entry" target="http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/874530">http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/874530</citedRange>
                  </bibl>
                </egXML>
                <p>A similar pattern may be used for other datasets, such as <title>Wikipedia</title>
                  (<ref target="http://syriaca.org/cbss/RNEJVB6D">http://syriaca.org/cbss/RNEJVB6D</ref>), which will have their own <title>CBSS</title> URIs:
                  <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                    <bibl xml:id="bib100-12">
                      <ptr target="http://syriaca.org/cbss/RNEJVB6D"/>
                      <citedRange unit="entry" target="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mount_Izla">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mount_Izla</citedRange>
                    </bibl>
                  </egXML>
                </p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          <div xml:id="relations">
            <head>Related Places</head>
            <p><emph>This element is not required. A record may have any number of <gi>relation</gi>
                elements.</emph></p>
            <p><title>TSG</title> uses the <gi>relation</gi> element (which must appear inside a
                single <gi>listRelation</gi> element immediately following the <gi>place</gi> element) to 
                record relations between a place record and other entities in the <ref target="#dataModel">Syriaca.org Knowledge Graph</ref>. The
                <gi>relation</gi> element must have a <att>type</att> attribute with one of the
              following values: "disambiguation", "contained-with", or "see-also". The use cases for each of these
              values are described below. Relations must also include <att>ref</att> attributes which take a 
              Syriaca.org Taxonomy URI defining the relationship, valid values of which are enumerated below. 
              The relation is expressed using either <att>active</att> and <att>passive</att> attributes, or a <att>mutual</att> attribute,
              which contain the Syriaca entity URIs for the related entities. Directed relationships, i.e. <code>Place A -> Place B</code>, are expressed
            using the <att>active</att>/<att>passive</att> attribute pair, while bi-direction relations, i.e., <code>Place A &lt;-&gt; Place B</code>
            are expressed using the <att>mutual</att> attribute. The specific relationship types described below determine which attributes
              should be used for the relationship. Finally, <gi>relation</gi> elements must be sourced as described in 
              <ref target="#source">Inserting Bibliographic Citations</ref>, though they commonly take a <att>resp</att> attribute as 
              described in <ref target="#resp">Asserting Information without a Source</ref>. In rare cases, they may include
              date attributes to qualify the time span during which a relation is valid (cf. <ref target="#dates">Recording Date Information for Occurrences and Durations</ref>).
            </p>
            <p>Common to all <gi>relation</gi> elements is a child <gi>desc</gi> element offering a
              human-readable version of the relationship. The <gi>desc</gi> element must have an <att>xml:lang</att> attribute 
              with the value of "en" for "English". A generic example of a relation follows, though see below for the 
            specific combination of values to use in the various relationship cases:
              <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                <relation type="contained-within" ref="http://syriaca.org/taxonomy/broader" active="http://syriaca.org/place/78" passive="http://syriaca.org/place/145" source="#bib78-1" to="0641">
                  <desc xml:lang="en">
                    <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/145">Osrhoene</placeName>
                  </desc>
                </relation>
              </egXML>
            </p>
            <div xml:id="disambiguation">
              <head>Disambiguating Places</head>
              <p>This relationship is used to explicitly declare a distinction between two
                places, especially when users might confuse them. There are four distinct kinds of scenarios for place
                disambiguation: places that share a name, conceptually related places, co-located
                places, and places easily confused for one another. These relations must have
               a <att>type</att> attribute value of "disambiguation".</p>
              <p><title>TSG</title> uses a URI from the <title>Syriac Taxonomy</title> to indicate
                which of these types of disambiguation is appropriate. This appears at the value of
                a <att>ref</att> attribute. The values are as follows: <table rows="5" cols="2">
                  <head>Disambiguation Values</head>
                  <row role="label">
                    <cell role="label">Reason for Disambiguation</cell>
                    <cell role="label">Value on the <att>ref</att> Attribute</cell>
                  </row>
                  <row role="data">
                    <cell role="data">Places that Share a Name</cell>
                    <cell role="data">http://syriaca.org/taxonomy/share-a-name</cell>
                  </row>
                  <row role="data">
                    <cell role="data">Conceptually Related Places</cell>
                    <cell role="data">http://syriaca.org/taxonomy/conceptually-related</cell>
                  </row>
                  <row role="data">
                    <cell role="data">Co-located Places</cell>
                    <cell role="data">http://syriaca.org/taxonomy/co-located</cell>
                  </row>
                  <row role="data">
                    <cell role="data">Places Easily Confused</cell>
                    <cell role="data">http://syriaca.org/taxonomy/not-to-be-confused-with</cell>
                  </row>
                </table>
              </p>
              <p>For all of the disambiguation relationships, the <gi>relation</gi> element requires
                a <att>mutual</att> attribute. A <att>mutual</att> attribute takes two or more space-separated place URIs. </p>
              <div xml:id="share-a-name">
                <head>Places That Share a Name</head>
                <p>There are many places that share a name. Syriaca.org only assigns URIs to
                  distinct entities so when there are two place records it can be assumed that the
                  editors are confident in the existence of two distinct places. However, it is helpful for
                  users to to find the specific place they are looking for if they have easy access
                  to multiple records for places that share a name. </p>
                <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                  <relation type="disambiguation" ref="http://syriaca.org/taxonomy/share-a-name"
                    mutual="http://syriaca.org/place/32 http://syriaca.org/place/717"
                    resp="http://syriaca.org">
                    <desc xml:lang="en">This place shares a name with one or more distinct
                      places.</desc>
                  </relation>
                </egXML>
              </div>
              <div xml:id="conceptually-related">
                <head>Conceptually Related Places</head>
                <p><title>TSG</title> distinguishes between place types. This can cause confusion for users when
                  different place types are closely related conceptually. For example, a city gives
                  its name to a diocese even though the diocese has a very different geographic
                  footprint than that city. They are two entities but closely related. Sources
                  can also talk about regions in ways that do not correspond entirely
                  to the geo-political entity with which it shares a name. For this reason, <title>TSG</title>
                  distinguishes between a region and a political province. To aid users in these cases, a disambiguation
                  relation may be created to make explicit the distinction between conceptually related places
                  See the code example below. </p> <!-- WLP: add an example for settlement/diocese -->
                <p><emph>This relationship has not yet been implemented in
                    <title>TSG</title>.</emph></p>
              </div>
              <div xml:id="co-located">
                <head>Co-located Places</head>
                <p>This relationship is used to help distinguish between two places that can be
                  confused based on closely sharing a location.</p>
                <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                  <relation type="disambiguation" ref="http://syriaca.org/taxonomy/co-located"
                    mutual="http://syriaca.org/place/2407 http://syriaca.org/place/791 http://syriaca.org/place/207"
                    resp="http://syriaca.org">
                    <desc xml:lang="en"> This place shares a location with one or more distinct
                      places that should not be confused with one another.</desc>
                  </relation>
                </egXML>
              </div>
              <div xml:id="not-to-be-confused-with">
                <head>Places Easily Confused</head>
                <p>For other general cases requiring a disambiguation relationship, a "not-to-be-confused"
                  relation should be asserted. This relation can be used to distinguish
                  between entities that have been confused in the scholarly literature or might be
                  confused by users for any reason.</p>
                <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                  <relation type="disambiguation"
                    ref="http://syriaca.org/taxonomy/not-to-be-confused-with"
                    mutual="http://syriaca.org/place/509 http://syriaca.org/place/111"
                    resp="http://syriaca.org">
                    <desc type="note" xml:lang="en"> Not the same conceptual place as <placeName
                        ref="http://syriaca.org/place/111">Kashkar</placeName>. </desc>
                  </relation>
                </egXML>
              </div>
            </div>
            <div xml:id="contained-within">
              <head>Places Contained Within Places</head>
              <p>This relationship is used to indicate that a place is contained within another
                place. It can be used for a church inside a city or a city inside a province. </p>
              <p>For a containment relationship, the <gi>relation</gi> element must have a
                <att>type</att> attribute value of "contained-within". Moreover, these relations use an
                  <att>active</att> and a <att>passive</att> attribute instead of a
                  <att>mutual</att> attribute. The URI for the place contained (smaller geographic boundaries) must be the value of the
                  <att>active</att> attribute and the URI for the place containing it (larger geographic boundaries) must be the value
                of the <att>passive</att> attribute. Containment relationships must include a <att>ref</att>
                attribute whose value is "http://syriaca.org/taxonomy/broader"</p>
              <p>The following example demonstrates a relation asserting that Ishtazin (<ref target="http://syriaca.org/place/758">http://syriaca.org/place/758</ref>)
                is contained within the Hakkārī region (<ref target="http://syriaca.org/place/90">http://syriaca.org/place/90</ref>)
              <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                <relation type="contained-within" ref="http://syriaca.org/taxonomy/broader"
                  active="http://syriaca.org/place/758" passive="http://syriaca.org/place/90"
                  source="#bib758-1">
                  <desc xml:lang="en">
                    <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/90">Hakkārī region</placeName>
                  </desc>
                </relation>
              </egXML>
              </p>
            </div>
            <div xml:id="see-also">
              <head>See Also</head>
              <p>This relationship is the most generic way of indicating a cross-reference within
                  <title>TSG</title>. It can be used to aid users in finding additional relevant place records
                based on their interest in the record where the "see-also" relation is asserted.
                This relation is used when two or more records are somehow related but that relationship cannot
                accurately be described using one of the relationships discussed above.</p>
              <p>This relationship must have a <att>type</att> attribute with the value of "see-also".
                Moreover, it takes a <att>mutual</att> attribute with two or more place URIs
                as the value to assert the places which are related. It must also include a 
                <att>ref</att> attribute with a value of "http://syriaca.org/taxonomy/related".</p>
              <egXML xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/Examples">
                <relation type="see-also" ref="http://syriaca.org/taxonomy/related"
                  mutual="http://syriaca.org/place/2615 http://syriaca.org/place/1535 http://syriaca.org/place/182 http://syriaca.org/place/58"
                  resp="http://syriaca.org">
                  <desc xml:lang="en">See also one or more related places.</desc>
                </relation>
              </egXML>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
      
      <div xml:id="schema">
        <head>NHSL TEI P5 Schema Customization</head>
        <schemaSpec ident="syriacaWorks" prefix="tei_" source="syriacaAll.compiled.odd" xml:lang="en" defaultExceptions="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0 teix:egXML​ http://www.example.org/ns/">
        <moduleRef key="core" include="author bibl biblScope citedRange date desc editor 
          foreign head label listBibl name note noteGrp p ptr quote ref resp respStmt textLang title"/>
        <moduleRef key="header" include="authority availability catDesc category 
          change classDecl edition editionStmt editorialDecl encodingDesc 
          fileDesc funder idno interpretation langUsage licence profileDesc 
          publicationStmt revisionDesc seriesStmt sourceDesc sponsor taxonomy
          teiHeader titleStmt"/>
        <moduleRef key="namesdates" include="listRelation persName placeName relation"/>
        <moduleRef key="tei"/>
        <moduleRef key="textstructure" include="body text TEI"/>
        <classRef key="att.personal"/>
        <classRef key="att.global.analytic"/>
        <classRef key="att.global.change"/>
        <classRef key="att.global.linking"/>
        
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="author" module="core" mode="change">
          <constraintSpec ident="ref-on-author" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body/child::tei:bibl/child::tei:author">
                <sch:assert test="matches(@ref, concat('http://syriaca.org/person/', '\d+'))" role="error">
                  This &lt;author&gt; element must take a @ref attribute 
                  with a Syriaca.org person URI which reqires 
                  the form 'http://syriaca.org/person/{\d+}' (where {\d+} is a number).
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
          <constraintSpec ident="author-in-context" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body/child::tei:bibl/child::tei:author">
                <sch:report test="tei:persName">
                  This &lt;author&gt; element allows only a text node with an English name 
                  or a &lt;foreign&gt; element with a non-English name.
                </sch:report>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <!--<elementSpec ident="authority" module="header" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>
          
          
          
          <elementSpec ident="availability" module="header" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>-->
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="bibl" module="core" mode="change">
          <content>
            <sequence preserveOrder="true">
              <elementRef key="title" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="author" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="editor" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="idno" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="label" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="ptr" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="citedRange" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="biblScope" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="textLang" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="date" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="noteGrp" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="note" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="listRelation" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="listBibl" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
            </sequence>
          </content>
          <constraintSpec ident="bibl-in-context" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:listBibl[@type='manuscripts']/tei:bibl">
                <sch:assert test="tei:label">
                  <!-- Add the requirement of a ptr once we have those mss records in place. -->
                  A manuscript &lt;bibl&gt; element must have a child &lt;label&gt; element.
                </sch:assert>
                <sch:assert test="@type='syriaca:Manuscript'">
                  This &lt;bibl&gt; element requires a @type attribute with the value "syriaca:Manuscript".
                </sch:assert>
                <sch:report test="@ana">
                  The @ana attribute is not allowed here.
                </sch:report>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:listBibl[@type='ancientVersions']/tei:bibl">
                <sch:assert test="tei:label or tei:ptr">
                  An ancient versions &lt;bibl&gt; element must have eith a child &lt;label&gt; element
                  or a child &lt;ptr&lt; element.
                </sch:assert>
                <sch:assert test="@type='syriaca:AncientVersion'">
                  This &lt;bibl&gt; element requires a @type attribute with the value "syriaca:AncientVersion".
                </sch:assert>
                <sch:report test="@ana">
                  The @ana attribute is not allowed here.
                </sch:report>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:listBibl[@type='editions']/tei:bibl">
                <sch:assert test="@type='lawd:Edition'">
                  This &lt;bibl&gt; element requires a @type attribute with the value "lawd:Edition".
                </sch:assert>
                <sch:assert test="tei:ptr">
                  An edition &lt;bibl&gt; element must have a child &lt;ptr&gt; element.
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:listBibl[@type='modernTranslations']/tei:bibl">
                <sch:assert test="@type='syriaca:ModernTranslation'">
                  This &lt;bibl&gt; element requires a @type attribute with the value "syriaca:ModernTranslation".
                </sch:assert>
                <sch:assert test="tei:ptr or tei:label">
                  A modern translation &lt;bibl&gt; element must have either a child &lt;ptr&gt; element or
                  a child &lt;label&gt; element. The &lt;label&gt; element should only be used in the 
                  rare instance where the modern translation is contained in a manuscript.
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:listBibl[@type='secondaryLiterature']/tei:bibl">
                <sch:assert test="@type='lawd:Citation'">
                  This &lt;bibl&gt; element requires a @type attribute with the value "lawd:Citation".
                </sch:assert>
                <sch:assert test="tei:ptr">
                  A secondary literature &lt;bibl&gt; element must have a child &lt;ptr&gt; element.
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body/child::tei:bibl">
                <sch:assert test="tei:title and tei:idno and tei:listBibl">
                  Every work-level &lt;bibl&gt; element must have as child elements at least &lt;title&gt;, 
                  &lt;idno&gt;, and &lt;listBibl&gt;.
                </sch:assert>
                <sch:report test="tei:note">
                  Notes under a work &lt;bibl&gt; must be encoded in a &lt;noteGrp&gt; element.
                </sch:report>
                <sch:report test="tei:bibl">
                  Bibliography under a work &lt;bibl&gt; must be encoded in a &lt;listBibl&gt; element.
                </sch:report>
                <sch:report test="tei:label">
                  The work &lt;bibl&gt; does not take a child &lt;label&gt; element.
                </sch:report>
                <sch:assert test="@xml:id">
                  The main work &lt;bibl&gt; must have an @xml:id.
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body/child::tei:bibl/@xml:id">
                <sch:let name="docURIno" value="replace(//tei:publicationStmt/tei:idno[@type='URI'][not(@type='deprecated')]/text(), '.+?(\d+).+', '$1')"/>
                <sch:let name="id" value="@xml:id"/>
                <sch:assert test="matches(., concat('work-', $docURIno))">
                  The required @xml:id must be 'work-<sch:value-of select="$docURIno"/>.
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:listBibl//tei:bibl">
                <sch:let name="docURIno" value="replace(//tei:publicationStmt/tei:idno[@type='URI'][not(@type='deprecated')]/text(), '.+?(\d+).+', '$1')"/>
                <sch:let name="id" value="@xml:id"/>
                <!-- The following rule isn't working to require an @xml:id on all listBibl/bibl elements. Should it? -->
                <sch:assert test="matches(./@xml:id, concat('bib', $docURIno, '-', '\d+$'))">
                  The required @xml:id must be 'bib<sch:value-of select="$docURIno"/>-{\d+}' (where {\d+} is a number).
                </sch:assert>
                <sch:report test="preceding-sibling::element()[@xml:id = $id]">This @xml:id is already in use.</sch:report>
                <sch:report test="tei:noteGrp">
                  Notes encoded inside a &lt;listBibl&gt; cannot appear inside a &lt;noteGrp&gt; element.
                </sch:report>
                <sch:report test="tei:listBibl">
                  Bibliography encoded inside a &lt;listBibl&gt; cannot appear inside a &lt;listBibl&gt; element.
                </sch:report>
                <sch:report test="tei:idno">
                  In this context, a &lt;idno&gt; element must appear as the child of a 
                  &lt;label&gt; element.
                </sch:report>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
          <constraintSpec ident="work-bhse" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body/child::tei:bibl[contains(@ana, '#syriaca-hagiographic')]">
                <sch:assert test="//tei:seriesStmt/tei:title = 'Bibliotheca Hagiographica Syriaca Electronica'">
                  This work record must include a &lt;seriesStmt&gt; indicating that it is part of the volume 
                  "Bibliotheca Hagiographica Syriaca Electronica".
                </sch:assert>
                <sch:assert test="//tei:seriesStmt/tei:title = 'Gateway to the Syriac Saints'">
                  This work record must include a &lt;seriesStmt&gt; indicating that it is part of the 
                  series "Gateway to the Syriac Saints".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:TEI[//tei:seriesStmt/tei:title = 'Gateway to the Syriac Saints']//tei:body/child::tei:bibl">
                <sch:assert test="contains(@ana, '#syriaca-hagiographic')">
                  A work &lt;bibl&gt; that is part of the series "Gateway to the Syriac Saints" must have an 
                  @ana attribute with the value "#syriaca-hagiographic".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:TEI[//tei:seriesStmt/tei:title = 'Bibliotheca Hagiographica Syriaca Electronica']//tei:body/child::tei:bibl">
                <sch:assert test="contains(@ana, '#syriaca-hagiographic')">
                  A work &lt;bibl&gt; that is part of the series "Bibliotheca Hagiographica Syriaca Electronica" must have an 
                  @ana attribute with the value "#syriaca-hagiographic".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
          <constraintSpec ident="work-bible" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body/child::tei:bibl[contains(@ana, '#syriaca-biblical')]">
                <sch:assert test="//tei:seriesStmt/tei:title = 'A Guide to the Bible in Syriac'">
                  This work record must include a &lt;seriesStmt&gt; indicating that it is part of the volume 
                  "A Guide to the Bible in Syriac".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:TEI[//tei:seriesStmt/tei:title = 'A Guide to the Bible in Syriac']//tei:body/child::tei:bibl">
                <sch:assert test="contains(@ana, '#syriaca-biblical')">
                  A work &lt;bibl&gt; that is part of the series "A Guide to the Bible in Syriac" must have an 
                  @ana attribute with the value "#syriaca-biblical".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
          <constraintSpec ident="work-science" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body/child::tei:bibl[contains(@ana, '#syriaca-scientific')]">
                <sch:assert test="//tei:seriesStmt/tei:title = 'Syriac Scientific and Philosophical Literature'">
                  This work record must include a &lt;seriesStmt&gt; indicating that it is part of the volume 
                  "Syriac Scientific and Philosophical Literature".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:TEI[//tei:seriesStmt/tei:title = 'Syriac Scientific and Philosophical Literature']//tei:body/child::tei:bibl">
                <sch:assert test="contains(@ana, '#syriaca-scientific')">
                  A work &lt;bibl&gt; that is part of the series "Syriac Scientific and Philosophical Literature" must have an 
                  @ana attribute with the value "#syriaca-scientific".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
          <constraintSpec ident="bibl-child-bibl" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:bibl//tei:bibl">
                <sch:report test="tei:listBibl">
                  This &lt;bibl&gt; element cannot take a child &lt;listBibl&gt;.
                </sch:report>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
          <attList>
            <attDef ident="type" mode="replace">
              <valList type="closed">
                <valItem ident="lawd:Citation"/>
                <valItem ident="lawd:Edition"/>
                <valItem ident="lawd:ConceptualWork"/>
                <valItem ident="lawd:Edition"/>
                <valItem ident="syriaca:AncientVersion"/>
                <valItem ident="syriaca:DigitalCatalog"/>
                <valItem ident="syriaca:LiteraryTradition"/>
                <valItem ident="syriaca:Manuscript"/>
                <valItem ident="syriaca:ModernTranslation"/>
                <valItem ident="syriaca:PrintCatalog"/>
              </valList>
            </attDef>
            <attDef ident="ana" mode="change">
              <!-- Not sure we want to do this? -->
              <valList type="closed">
                <valItem ident="#syriaca-biblical"/>
                <valItem ident="#syriaca-hagiographic"/>
                <valItem ident="#syriaca-scientific"/>
              </valList>
            </attDef>
          </attList>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="biblScope" module="core" mode="change">
          
          <content>
            <sequence preserveOrder="false">
              <textNode/>
              <elementRef key="idno" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="title" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
            </sequence>
          </content>
          <attList>
            <attDef ident="unit" mode="change" usage="req">
              <valList type="closed" mode="replace">
                <valItem ident="cah"/>
                <valItem ident="fol"/>
                <valItem ident="p"/>
                <valItem ident="vol"/>
              </valList>
            </attDef>
            <!-- Look into @n, @from, @to -->
          </attList>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="body" module="textstructure" mode="change">
          <content>
            <elementRef key="bibl" minOccurs="1" maxOccurs="1"/>
          </content>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="catDesc" module="header" mode="change">
          
          <content>
            <sequence preserveOrder="false">
              <textNode/>
              <elementRef key="ref" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
            </sequence>
          </content>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="category" module="header" mode="change">
          
          <content>
            <elementRef key="catDesc" minOccurs="1"/>
          </content>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="change" module="header" mode="change">
          
          <content>
            <sequence preserveOrder="false">
              <textNode/>
              <elementRef key="ref" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
            </sequence>
          </content>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <!--<elementSpec ident="citedRange" module="core" mode="change">
          
          
          </elementSpec>-->
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="classDecl" module="header" mode="change">
          <content>
            <elementRef key="taxonomy" minOccurs="1" maxOccurs="1"/>
          </content>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="date" module="core" mode="change">
          <content>
            <textNode/>
          </content>
          <attList>
            <!-- Regarding @calendar and @datingMethod, see SPEAR ODD -->
            <attDef ident="type" mode="change" usage="rec">
              <!-- might need to revisit this -->
              <desc>specifies how the date is associated with the work to
                which it refers</desc>
              <valList mode="replace" type="closed">
                <valItem ident="original-composition">
                  <desc>the date a work was originally composed</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="revision">
                  <desc>the date a work was revised</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="translation">
                  <desc>the date a work was translated</desc>
                </valItem>
              </valList>
            </attDef>
          </attList>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="desc" module="core" mode="change">
          <content>
            <sequence preserveOrder="false">
              <textNode/>
              <elementRef key="label" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="1"/>
              <elementRef key="persName" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="1"/>
              <elementRef key="placeName" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="1"/>
              <elementRef key="title" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="1"/>
            </sequence>
          </content>
          <constraintSpec ident="noteGrp-desc-values" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:noteGrp[@type='abstract']/tei:desc">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'Abstract'">Text node must be "Abstract".</sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:noteGrp[@type='contents']/tei:desc">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'Contents'">Text node must be "Contents".</sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:noteGrp[@type='excerpts']/tei:desc">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'Excerpts'">Text node must be "Excerpts".</sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:noteGrp[@type='disambiguation']/tei:desc">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'Disambiguation'">Text node must be "Disambiguation".</sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:noteGrp[@type='excerpts']/tei:desc">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'Excerpts'">Text node must be "Excerpt".</sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:noteGrp[@type='explicit']/tei:desc">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'Explicit'">Text node must be "Explicit".</sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:noteGrp[@type='incipit']/tei:desc">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'Incipit'">Text node must be "Incipit".</sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:noteGrp[@type='prologue']/tei:desc">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'Prologue'">Text node must be "Prologue".</sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:noteGrp[@type='scope']/tei:desc">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'Scope'">Text node must be "Scope".</sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:noteGrp[@type='versions']/tei:desc">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'Ancient Versions'">Text node must be "Versions".</sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <!--<elementSpec ident="editionStmt" module="header" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>-->
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="editor" module="core" mode="change">
          <constraintSpec ident="ref-on-editor" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body/child::tei:bibl/child::tei:editor">
                <sch:assert test="matches(@ref, concat('http://syriaca.org/person/', '\d+'))" role="error">
                  This &lt;editor&gt; element must take a @ref attribute 
                  with a Syriaca.org person URI which reqires 
                  the form 'http://syriaca.org/person/{\d+}' (where {\d+} is a number).
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
          <constraintSpec ident="editor-in-context" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body/child::tei:bibl/child::tei:editor">
                <sch:report test="tei:persName">
                  This &lt;author&gt; element allows only a text node with an English name 
                  or a &lt;foreign&gt; element with a non-English name.
                </sch:report>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <!--<elementSpec ident="editorialDecl" module="header" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>-->
        
        
        
        <!--<elementSpec ident="encodingDesc" module="header" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>-->
        
        
        
        <!--<elementSpec ident="fileDesc" module="header" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>-->
        
        
        
        <!--<elementSpec ident="foreign" module="core" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>-->
        
        
        
        <!--<elementSpec ident="funder" module="header" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>-->
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="head" module="core" mode="change">
          <content>
            <textNode/>
          </content>
          <constraintSpec ident="listBibl-head-values" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='editions']/tei:head">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'Editions'">Text node must be "Editions".</sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='manuscripts']/tei:head">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'Manuscripts'">Text node must be "Manuscripts".</sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='modernTranslations']/tei:head">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'Modern Translations'">Text node must be "Modern Translations".</sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='ancientVersions']/tei:head">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'Ancient Versions'">Text node must be "Ancient Version".</sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='secondaryLiterature']/tei:head">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'Secondary Literature'">Text node must be "Secondary Literature".</sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="idno" module="header" mode="change">
          <content>
            <textNode/>
          </content>
          <constraintSpec ident="work-idno-types" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body/child::tei:bibl/child::tei:idno/@type">
                <sch:assert test=". = ('deprecated', 'number', 'URI', 'URN')">
                  The only acceptable values for @type on a work &lt;idno&gt; are "deprecated", "number", 
                  "URI" or "URN". 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body/child::tei:bibl/child::tei:idno[1]">
                <sch:let name="workURI" value="substring-before(//tei:publicationStmt/tei:idno[@type='URI'][not(@type='deprecated')]/text(), '/tei')"/>
                <sch:assert test=". = $workURI">
                  The text node of this &lt;idno&gt; element must be <sch:value-of select="$workURI"/>. 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='manuscripts']/tei:bibl/tei:label/tei:idno/@type">
                <sch:assert test=". = ('accession-number', 'catalog-number', 'number', 'project-number', 'shelfmark', 'URL')">
                  In the context of manuscripts, this @type value may only be "accession-number", "number",
                  "project-number", or "shelfmark". 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='manuscripts']/tei:bibl/tei:label/tei:idno[@subtype='Bekker' or @subtype='CPG' or @subtype='Fichtner']/@type">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'number'">
                  When an &lt;indo&gt; has @subtype="<sch:value-of select="./parent::tei:idno/@subtype"/>", 
                  the @type value must be "number".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='manuscripts']/tei:bibl/tei:label/tei:idno[@subtype='BAV' or @subtype='BML' or @subtype='UCL']/@type">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'shelfmark'">
                  When an &lt;indo&gt; has @subtype="<sch:value-of select="./parent::tei:idno/@subtype"/>", 
                  the @type value must be "shelfmark".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='manuscripts']/tei:bibl/tei:label/tei:idno[@subtype='HMML']/@type">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'project-number'">
                  When an &lt;indo&gt; has @subtype="<sch:value-of select="./parent::tei:idno/@subtype"/>", 
                  the @type value must be "project-number".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='manuscripts']/tei:bibl/tei:label/tei:idno[@subtype='Rosen']/@type">
                <sch:assert test=". = 'catalog-number'">
                  When an &lt;indo&gt; has @subtype="<sch:value-of select="./parent::tei:idno/@subtype"/>", 
                  the @type value must be "catalog-number".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
          <constraintSpec ident="idno-subtypes" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body/child::tei:bibl/child::tei:idno[@type='number']/@subtype">
                <sch:assert test=". = ('Bekker', 'BHO', 'BHS', 'CPG', 'Fichtner', 'Kühn', 'Takahashi')">
                  The only acceptable values for @subtype on a work &lt;idno&gt; with @type="number" are 
                  "Bekker", "BHO", "BHS", "CPG", "Fichtner", "Kühn", and "Takahashi". 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='manuscripts']/tei:bibl/tei:label/tei:idno/@subtype" role="warning">
                <sch:assert test=". = ('BAV', 'BL', 'BML', 'BNF', 'Berlin', 'Cambridge', 'Crawford', 'Haddad-Isaac', 'Harris', 'HMML', 'Leiden', 'Mingana', 'Rosen', 'SOAH', 'Sachau', 'Sinai', 'UCL')">
                  In the context of manuscripts, this @subtype value may only be 
                  "BAV" (for the Vatican Apostolic Library), "BML" (for The Laurentian Library), 
                  "Berlin", "Cambridge", "Crawford", "Haddad-Isaac", "Harris", "HMML", 
                  "Leiden", "Mingana", "Rosen", "SOAH", "Sachau", or "UCL". 
                  If none of these options is correct, please write in an appropriate
                  value and the warning message will prompt editors to ensure that it is the correct value.
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
          <attList>
            <attDef ident="type" mode="change" usage="req">
              <desc>The <att>type</att> attribute on <gi>idno</gi> defines the kind of identifier contained in the text value.</desc>
              <valList mode="replace" type="closed">
                <valItem ident="accession-number"/>
                <valItem ident="catalog-number"/>
                <valItem ident="deprecated"/>
                <valItem ident="number"/>
                <valItem ident="project-number"/>
                <valItem ident="shelfmark"/>
                <valItem ident="URI"/>
                <valItem ident="URL"/>
                <valItem ident="URN"/>
              </valList>
            </attDef>
            <attDef ident="subtype" mode="change" usage="opt">
              <valList mode="replace" type="semi">
                <valItem ident="BAV"/>
                <valItem ident="Bekker"/>
                <valItem ident="Berlin"/>
                <valItem ident="BHS"/>
                <valItem ident="BHO"/>
                <valItem ident="BL"/>
                <valItem ident="BML"/>
                <valItem ident="BNF"/>
                <valItem ident="Cambridge"/>
                <valItem ident="CPG"/>
                <valItem ident="Crawford"/>
                <valItem ident="Fichtner"/>
                <valItem ident="Haddad-Isaac"/>
                <valItem ident="Harris"/>
                <valItem ident="Kühn"/>
                <valItem ident="Leiden"/>
                <valItem ident="Mingana"/>
                <valItem ident="Rosen"/>
                <valItem ident="Takashi"/>
                <valItem ident="Sachau"/>
                <valItem ident="SOAH"/>
                <valItem ident="Sinai"/>
              </valList>
            </attDef>
          </attList>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <!--<elementSpec ident="interpretation" module="header" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>-->
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="label" module="core" mode="change">
          <content>
            <sequence preserveOrder="true">
              <textNode/>
              <elementRef key="idno" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="ptr" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="1"/>
              <elementRef key="title" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="1"/>
            </sequence>
          </content>
          <constraintSpec ident="ptr-with-label" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:label[not(ancestor::tei:relation)]">
                <sch:report test="tei:ptr">
                  A &lt;ptr&gt; child of &lt;label&gt; should only be used
                  when &lt;label&gt; is the descendant of &lt;relation&gt;.
                </sch:report>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
          <constraintSpec ident="label-values" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='manuscripts']/bibl/label[idno/@subtype='Bekker']">
                <sch:assert test="starts-with(., 'Bekker')">
                  This text should begin "Bekker". 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='manuscripts']/bibl/label[idno/@subtype='BML']">
                <sch:assert test="starts-with(., 'The Laurentian Library')">
                  This text should begin "The Laurentian Library". 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='manuscripts']/bibl/label[idno/@subtype='Fichtner']">
                <sch:assert test="starts-with(., 'Fichtner')">
                  This text should begin "Fichtner". 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='manuscripts']/bibl/label[idno/@subtype='HMML']">
                <sch:assert test="starts-with(., 'Hill Museum and Manuscript Library')">
                  This text should begin "Hill Museum and Manuscript Library". 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='manuscripts']/bibl/label[idno/@subtype='Kühn']">
                <sch:assert test="starts-with(., 'Kühn')">
                  This text should begin "Kühn". 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='manuscripts']/bibl/label[idno/@subtype='Rosen']">
                <sch:assert test="starts-with(., 'Rosen')">
                  This text should begin "Rosen". 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='manuscripts']/bibl/label[idno/@subtype='Takahashi']">
                <sch:assert test="starts-with(., 'Takahashi')">
                  This text should begin "Takahashi". 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='manuscripts']/bibl/label[idno/@subtype='UCL']">
                <sch:assert test="starts-with(., 'University College London')">
                  This text should begin "University College London". 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:listBibl[@type='manuscripts']/bibl/label[idno/@subtype='BAV']">
                <sch:assert test="starts-with(., 'Vatican Apostolic Library')">
                  This text should begin "The Vatican Apostolic Library". 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
          <!--<attList>
            <attDef ident="subtype" mode="change">
              <valList type="closed">
                <valItem ident="book"/>
                <valItem ident="collection"/>
                <valItem ident="part"/>
              </valList>
            </attDef>
            <attDef ident="type" mode="change">
              <valList type="closed">
                <valItem ident="order"/>
              </valList>
            </attDef>
          </attList>-->
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <!--<elementSpec ident="langUsage" module="header" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>-->
        
        
        
        <!--<elementSpec ident="licence" module="header" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>-->
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="listBibl" module="core" mode="change">
          <content>
            <sequence preserveOrder="true">
              <elementRef key="head" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="1"/>
              <elementRef key="desc" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="1"/>
              <elementRef key="bibl" minOccurs="1" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
            </sequence>
          </content>
          <constraintSpec ident="listBibl-in-body" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:listBibl">
                <sch:assert test="tei:head">
                  This &lt;listBibl&gt; requires a &lt;head&gt;.
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:listBibl">
                <sch:assert test="tei:desc">
                  This &lt;listBibl&gt; requires a &lt;desc&gt;.
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:listBibl">
                <sch:assert test="@type">
                  This &lt;listBibl&gt; requires a @type attribute.
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
          <attList>
            <attDef ident="type" mode="change" usage="rec">
              <valList type="closed">
                <valItem ident="editions"/>
                <valItem ident="manuscripts"/>
                <valItem ident="modernTranslations"/>
                <valItem ident="ancientVersions"/>
                <valItem ident="secondaryLiterature"/>
              </valList>
            </attDef>
          </attList>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <!--<elementSpec ident="listRelation" module="namesdates" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>-->
        
        
        
        <!--<elementSpec ident="name" module="core" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>-->
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="note" module="core" mode="change">
          <content>
            <sequence preserveOrder="false">
              <textNode/>
              <elementRef key="date" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="persName" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="placeName" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="quote" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="1"/>
              <elementRef key="ref" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="1"/>
              <elementRef key="title" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
            </sequence>
          </content>
          <constraintSpec ident="noteGrp-note-type" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:noteGrp[@type='abstract']/tei:note">
                <sch:assert test="@type='abstract'">
                  This &lt;note&gt; must contain a @type attribute with value "abstract".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:noteGrp[@type='content']/tei:note">
                <sch:assert test="@type='content'">
                  This &lt;note&gt; must contain a @type attribute with value "abstract".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:noteGrp[@type='disambiguation']/tei:note">
                <sch:assert test="@type='disambiguation'">
                  This &lt;note&gt; must contain a @type attribute with value "abstract".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:noteGrp[@type='exerpts']/tei:note">
                <sch:assert test="@type='exerpt'">
                  This &lt;note&gt; must contain a @type attribute with value "abstract".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:noteGrp[@type='explicit']/tei:note">
                <sch:assert test="@type='explicit'">
                  This &lt;note&gt; must contain a @type attribute with value "abstract".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:noteGrp[@type='incipit']/tei:note">
                <sch:assert test="@type='incipit'">
                  This &lt;note&gt; must contain a @type attribute with value "abstract".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:noteGrp[@type='prologue']/tei:note">
                <sch:assert test="@type='prologue'">
                  This &lt;note&gt; must contain a @type attribute with value "abstract".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:noteGrp[@type='scope']/tei:note">
                <sch:assert test="@type='scope'">
                  This &lt;note&gt; must contain a @type attribute with value "abstract".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:noteGrp[@type='versions']/tei:note">
                <sch:assert test="@type='version'">
                  This &lt;note&gt; must contain a @type attribute with value "abstract".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
          <constraintSpec ident="quotes-in-notes" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="
                tei:body//tei:note[@type=('excerpt','explicit','incipit','prologue')]">
                <sch:assert test="tei:quote and count(*) = count(tei:quote)">
                  When &lt;note&gt; has type excerpt, explicit, incipit, or prologue,
                  it must contain only &lt;quote&gt; elements.
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
          <constraintSpec ident="listBibl-note-type" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:bibl/tei:listBibl//tei:note">
                <sch:report test="@type">
                  This &lt;note&gt; element does not take a @type attribute.
                </sch:report>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
          <attList>
            <attDef ident="type" mode="change" usage="rec">
              <valList mode="add" type="closed">
                <valItem ident="abstract">
                  <desc>A note containing a brief description of the work.</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="content">
                  <desc>A note containing a brief summary of the content of the work.</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="disambiguation">
                  <desc>A note containing a brief discussion of how to distinguish this 
                    work from others with which it has been or could be confused.</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="excerpt">
                  <desc>A note containing an exerpt from the work.</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="explicit">
                  <desc>A note containing the ending of the work.</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="incipit">
                  <desc>A note containing the beginning of the work.</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="licence">
                  <desc>A note containing the licence. Used only in the TEI header.</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="prologue">
                  <desc>A note containing the prologue of the work.</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="scope">
                  <desc>A note describing the works relationship to larger works 
                    or collections containing it.</desc>
                </valItem>
                <valItem ident="version">
                  <desc>A note containing a brief summary of the versions of the work.</desc>
                </valItem>
              </valList>
            </attDef>
          </attList>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="noteGrp" module="core" mode="change">
          <content>
            <sequence preserveOrder="true">
              <elementRef key="desc" minOccurs="1" maxOccurs="1"/>
              <elementRef key="note" minOccurs="1" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
            </sequence>
          </content>
          <attList>
            <attDef ident="type" mode="change" usage="req">
              <valList type="closed">
                <valItem ident="abstract"/>
                <valItem ident="contents"/>
                <valItem ident="disambiguation"/>
                <valItem ident="excerpts"/>
                <valItem ident="explicit"/>
                <valItem ident="incipit"/>
                <valItem ident="prologue"/>
                <valItem ident="scope"/>
                <valItem ident="versions"/>
              </valList>
            </attDef>
          </attList>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="p" module="core" mode="change">
          
          <content>
            <sequence preserveOrder="false">
              <elementRef key="listBibl" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="1"/>
              <elementRef key="note" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <elementRef key="ref" minOccurs="0" maxOccurs="unbounded"/>
              <textNode/>
            </sequence>
          </content>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="persName" module="namesdates" mode="change">
          <constraintSpec ident="ref-on-persName" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:persName[not(parent::tei:author)]">
                <sch:assert test="matches(@ref, concat('http://syriaca.org/person/', '\d+'))" role="error">
                  This &lt;persName&gt; element must take a @ref attribute 
                  with a Syriaca.org person URI which reqires 
                  the form 'http://syriaca.org/person/{\d+}' (where {\d+} is a number).
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <!--<elementSpec ident="profileDesc" module="header" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>
          
          
          
          <elementSpec ident="ptr" module="core" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>
          
          
          
          <elementSpec ident="publicationStmt" module="header" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>
          
          
          
          <elementSpec ident="ref" module="core" mode="change">
          <!-\- Not sure the @target attribute needs to be constrained. -\->
          
          </elementSpec>-->
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="relation" module="namesdates" mode="change">
          <constraintSpec ident="passive-values" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="tei:body//tei:relation">
                <sch:report test="contains(., '\s')">
                  The @passive attribute may only take one value.
                </sch:report>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
          <attList>
            <attDef ident="name" mode="delete"/>
            <attDef ident="ref" mode="change" usage="req">
              <valList type="closed">
                <valItem ident="dcterms:isPartOf"/>
                <valItem ident="dcterms:source"/>
                <valItem ident="skos:broader"/>
                <valItem ident="syriaca:commemorates"/>
                <valItem ident="syriaca:different-from"/>
              </valList>
            </attDef>
          </attList>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
        <!--<elementSpec ident="resp" module="core" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>
          
          
          
          <elementSpec ident="respStmt" module="core" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>
          
          
          
          <elementSpec ident="revisionDesc" module="header" mode="change">
          
          </elementSpec>-->
        
        
        
        <elementSpec ident="seriesStmt" module="header" mode="change">
          <constraintSpec ident="seriesStmt-series" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="//tei:seriesStmt//tei:title[@level='s']">
                <sch:assert test="
                  ./node() = 'A New Handbook of Syriac Literature' or 
                  ./node() = 'Gateway to the Syriac Saints'"> 
                  This &lt;title&gt; element must be "A New Handbook of Syriac Literature" or 
                  "Gateway to the Syriac Saints". 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="//tei:seriesStmt[tei:title = 'A New Handbook of Syriac Literature']/tei:idno">
                <sch:assert test="matches(., 'http://syriaca.org/nhsl')">
                  This &lt;idno&gt; element must contain "http://syriaca.org/nhsl". 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="//tei:seriesStmt[tei:title = 'Gateway to the Syriac Saints']/tei:idno">
                <sch:assert test="matches(., 'http://syriaca.org/saints')">
                  This &lt;idno&gt; element must contain "http://syriaca.org/saints". 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
          <constraintSpec ident="seriesStmt-monograph" scheme="schematron">
            <constraint>
              <sch:rule context="//tei:seriesStmt//tei:title[@level='m']">
                <sch:assert test="
                  ./node() = 'Bibliotheca Hagiographica Syriaca Electronica' or
                  ./node() = 'A Guide to the Bible in Syriac' or
                  ./node() = 'Syriac Scientific and Philosophical Literature'"> 
                  This &lt;title&gt; element must be 
                  "Bibliotheca Hagiographica Syriaca Electronica" or
                  "Guide to the Bible in Syriac" or 
                  "Syriac Scientific and Philosophical Literature". 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="//tei:seriesStmt[tei:title = 'Bibliotheca Hagiographica Syriaca Electronica']/tei:idno">
                <sch:assert test="matches(., 'http://syriaca.org/bhse')">
                  This &lt;idno&gt; element must contain "http://syriaca.org/bhse". 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="//tei:seriesStmt[tei:title='Bibliotheca Hagiographica Syriaca Electronica']">
                <sch:assert test="tei:biblScope/@n = '1'">
                  Requires a &lt;biblScope&gt; element with @n="1" since "Bibliotheca Hagiographica Syriaca Electronica" is volume 1 of 
                  "A New Handbook of Syriac Literature".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="//tei:seriesStmt[tei:title = 'A Guide to the Bible in Syriac']/tei:idno">
                <sch:assert test="matches(., 'http://syriaca.org/bible')">
                  This &lt;idno&gt; element must contain "http://syriaca.org/bible". 
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
              <sch:rule context="//tei:seriesStmt[tei:title='A Guide to the Bible in Syriac']">
                <sch:assert test="tei:biblScope/@n = '2'">
                  Requires a &lt;biblScope&gt; element with @n="2" since "A Guide to the Bible in Syriac" is volume 2 of 
                  "A New Handbook of Syriac Literature".
                </sch:assert>
              </sch:rule>
            </constraint>
          </constraintSpec>
        </elementSpec>
        
        
        
